The Cliffordization routine employed by ",["$","code",null,{"children":"Neat","className":"text-code-02 inline whitespace-nowrap px-4 bg-background border border-transparent dark:border-border-subtle-00 group-[.pre-el]:text-code-02 group-[.pre-el]:inline-block group-[.pre-el]:whitespace-pre group-[.pre-el]:p-12 group-[.pre-el]:pr-[50px] group-[.pre-el]:bg-inherit dark:group-[.pre-el]:border-transparent group-[.paragraph-el]:whitespace-normal"}]," is the ",["$","$L15",null,{"children":["$","code",null,{"children":"to_clifford","className":"text-code-02 inline whitespace-nowrap px-4 bg-background border border-transparent dark:border-border-subtle-00 group-[.pre-el]:text-code-02 group-[.pre-el]:inline-block group-[.pre-el]:whitespace-pre group-[.pre-el]:p-12 group-[.pre-el]:pr-[50px] group-[.pre-el]:bg-inherit dark:group-[.pre-el]:border-transparent group-[.paragraph-el]:whitespace-normal"}],"href":"/api/qiskit-ibm-runtime/qiskit_ibm_runtime.debug_tools.Neat#to_clifford","className":"text-link-primary no-underline hover:underline inline"}]," method.  It performs minimal modifications to the original circuit. In particular, it replaces non-Clifford single-qubit gates in the original circuit with Clifford single-qubit gates, but it does not mutate the two-qubit gates, number of qubits, and circuit depth. In this way, the original circuit and the resulting Clifford circuit suffer similar levels of noise, and the Clifford circuit can be used as a proxy to study the original circuit of interest."],"className":"group paragraph-el text-text-primary mx-0"}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":[["$","code",null,{"children":"Neat","className":"text-code-02 inline whitespace-nowrap px-4
